<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900523-0049</DOCNO><DOCID>900523-0049.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>05/23/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   TREASURY CHIEF BRADY will ask Congress today for massivenew borrowing authority to finance the Sandamp;L bailout, officialssaid. The secretary is expected to acknowledge that hisdepartment badly underestimated the cost of the thrift rescueand to seek authority to borrow $80 billion to $140 billion.The new estimates could put the bailout's total cost totaxpayers at $300 billion over 10 years.                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   Thrift regulators' new tactic of selling Sandamp;Ls in pieceshas sharply increased the short-term cost of the bailout. Theapproach is threatening to swell the budget deficit andhasten the thrift industry's demise.   ---   TWA slashed round-trip fares on domestic flights by up to30%, fueling an unexpected fare skirmish among airlines.United Air initiated the battle Monday when it ran adsoffering $35 off certain round-trip fares.                                                                                                          Safety seats should be required for small children on allairline flights, a federal board urged, which wouldeffectively end their free rides.   ---   Pinnacle West rejected PacifiCorp's $1.82 billion takeoveroffer as well as Salt River Project's $500 million bid forcertain assets. PacifiCorp said it is reviewing options,which could include directly approaching Pinnacleshareholders.   ---   Citicorp's credit ratings were lowered by Moody's,including the rating on commercial paper. Sandamp;P made a similarmove last month but affirmed Citicorp's commercial-paperrating.   ---   The U.S. criticized Japan for the slow pace of financialderegulation. Tokyo also was warned it may face tradesanctions unless it agrees soon to decontrol bank depositrates.   ---   Federal Express stock slid nearly 10%, to $47, after thefirm disclosed that shipment growth slowed sharply in April.Recent company statements had prompted analysts to predict aturnaround in the current quarter.   ---   A plan to give the SEC more clout, including oversight ofstock-index futures, will soon be unveiled by Bush officials.But support for the proposal appears to be waning inCongress.   ---   Exxon and Du Pont's Conoco unit settled allegations by aBermuda oil trading firm that they and six other oilcompanies rigged crude prices.   ---   Bond prices rallied on heavy foreign buying, which helpedlift stocks hurt by profit-taking. The Dow Jones industrialsclosed up 7.55 points, at a record 2852.23. The dollar wasmixed.   ---   Chrysler has stopped seeking a buyer for itsdefense-related operations, apparently because it didn't geta satisfactory offer. The auto maker said it will revamp andboost research and development funding at the unit.   ---   Greyhound's striking workers made an unconditional offerto return to work. But the move is intended to set the stagefor a potentially huge back-pay claim against the company.   ---   Eight publicly traded funds originally sponsored by VMSRealty Partners announced a return to profitability, butsharply cut their book values.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 203,350,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2852.23, up 7.55; transportation 1169.63, off 11.20;utilities 213.09, off 1.13.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3355.19, up24.05.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.52, up 0.43; spotindex 135.67, up 0.02.   Dollar: 151.20 yen, off 2.52; 1.6736 marks, up 0.0110.</TEXT></DOC>